<GAP DESC="illegible" EXTENT="1 letter">o ob&s;erve him in &s;ilence, concluding that
tho&s;e papers were letters of her late mo|ther.
Pre&s;ently he knelt down, and with
look &s;o &s;olemn as &s;he had &s;eldom &s;een him
a&s;&s;ume, and which was mingled with a cer|tain
wild expre&s;&s;ion, that partook more of
<GAP DESC="illegible" EXTENT="1 letter">orror than of any other character, he pray|<GAP DESC="illegible" EXTENT="1 letter">d
&s;ilently for a con&s;iderable time.</P>
<P>When he ro&s;e, a gha&s;tly palene&s;s was on
<GAP DESC="illegible" EXTENT="1 letter">is countenance. Emily was ha&s;tily retir|<GAP DESC="illegible" EXTENT="2 letters">g;
but &s;he &s;aw him turn again to the
<GAP DESC="illegible" EXTENT="1 letter">apers, and &s;he &s;topped. He took from
<GAP DESC="illegible" EXTENT="1 letter">mong them a &s;mall ca&s;e, and from thence
<GAP DESC="illegible" EXTENT="1 word"> miniature picture. The rays of light fell
