them, and returned a &s;ullen found, which
the echoes of the mountains prolonged.
Under the bridge was &s;een a per&s;pective of
the valley, with its cataract de&s;cending
among the rocks, and a cottage on a cliff,
over&s;hadowed with pines. It appeared,
that they could not be far from &s;ome &s;mall
town. St. Aubert bade the muleteer &s;top,
and then called to the children to enquire
<PB N="119" REF="129">
if he was near Montigny; but the di&s;tance,
