and Valancourt to explore new
&s;cenes among the mountains, on his return
home. During this evening he was often
<PB N="148" REF="158">
&s;ilent and thoughtful; St. Aubert's manner
towards him was affectionate, though grave,
and Emily was &s;erious, though &s;he made
frequent efforts to appear cheerful. After
one of the mo&s;t melancholy evenings they
